spec: ab3271
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(abc)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/abc.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 665 (ab3271): __rand__, __ror__, __rxor__ dict-presence (reflected bitwise logical) for abc module types."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: abc.ABC, abc.ABCMeta, and type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) — the built-in function type."
    - "Key finding (__rand__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __rand__. abc.ABC is a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no bitwise semantics — n & ABC is not a defined Python operation and ABC has no __rand__ to provide a fallback. abc.ABCMeta is a metaclass responsible for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass registration (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__); none of these capabilities involve reflected bitwise AND. The function type (type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>) does not define __rand__ — functions are callables and descriptors, not numeric or bitwise types. n & f is not a valid Python expression for function objects."
    - "Key finding (__ror__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __ror__. Reflected bitwise OR (__ror__) is invoked when the left operand's __or__ returns NotImplemented. abc.ABC defines no bitwise or logical operators — neither __or__ nor __ror__ appear in its __dict__. abc.ABCMeta's entire capability is in class-hierarchy machinery; reflected bitwise OR is entirely absent. The function type does not define __ror__; n | f is not a valid Python expression for callable objects. Note: Python 3.9+ dict defines __ror__ for the PEP 584 merge operator, but function objects and abc types are neither dict subclasses nor mapping types and do not implement this protocol."
    - "Key finding (__rxor__): all 3 abc subjects return false for __rxor__. Reflected bitwise XOR (__rxor__) is invoked when n ^ obj is attempted and the left operand does not handle the right operand. abc.ABC has no numeric, bitwise, or logical data model. abc.ABCMeta handles abstract method tracking and class hierarchy; none of its responsibilities map to reflected bitwise XOR. The function type does not define __rxor__; n ^ f is not a valid Python expression for callable objects."
    - "All 9 values in this wave are false — continuing the all-false pattern from wave 664 (__rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__)."
    - "The function type profile across all waves: true only for __get__ (wave 652), __repr__ (wave 655), and __call__ (wave 656). All other dunders tested — including this wave's __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ — are false."
    - "abc.ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic, bitwise, and reflected dunder tested across 14 consecutive waves (652–665). Its entire capability is expressed through class-hierarchy machinery, not operator overloading."
    - "Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:"
    - "  Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false."
    - "  Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false."
    - "  Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false."
    - "  Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 662 (ab3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 663 (ab3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 664 (ab3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 3."
    - "  Wave 665 (ab3271): __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ — all false for all 3."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __rand__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__rand__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __rand__.
# abc.ABC: a plain abstract base class convenience wrapper with no bitwise
#   or arithmetic semantics. n & ABC is not a defined Python operation;
#   ABC has no __rand__ to serve as a fallback.
# abc.ABCMeta: a metaclass for abstract method tracking and virtual subclass
#   registration. Reflected bitwise AND has no role in ABCMeta's
#   responsibilities (__subclasshook__, register(), __abstractmethods__).
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __rand__. n & f is not a valid Python
#   expression for callable objects. Functions are callables and descriptors
#   with no bitwise data model.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3271.rand:
  description: "abc types __rand__ dict-presence checks; wave 665"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3271

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3271001", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__rand__"], false]
    - ["ab3271002", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__rand__"], false]
    - ["ab3271003", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__rand__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __ror__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__ror__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __ror__.
# abc.ABC: no bitwise or logical data model; neither __or__ nor __ror__
#   appear in abc.ABC's __dict__. ABC is a pure abstract base class helper
#   with no state of its own beyond what ABCMeta provides.
# abc.ABCMeta: does not define __ror__ for metaclass reflected bitwise OR.
#   ABCMeta's API surface (__subclasshook__, register(),
#   __abstractmethods__) has no bitwise or logical operator component.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __ror__. n | f is not a valid Python expression
#   for callable objects. Note: Python 3.9+ dict defines __ror__ for the
#   PEP 584 merge operator (d2 | d1 where d2.__or__ returns NotImplemented),
#   but function objects are neither dict subclasses nor mapping types and
#   do not implement this protocol. The function type is tightly scoped to
#   its role as a callable descriptor with a display representation.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3271.ror:
  description: "abc types __ror__ dict-presence checks; wave 665"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3271

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3271004", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__ror__"], false]
    - ["ab3271005", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__ror__"], false]
    - ["ab3271006", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__ror__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __rxor__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__rxor__')
#
# All 3 abc subjects return false for __rxor__.
# abc.ABC: no numeric, bitwise, or logical data model; n ^ ABC is not a
#   defined Python expression. abc.ABC is a bare metaclass convenience
#   wrapper with no state of its own beyond what ABCMeta provides.
# abc.ABCMeta: does not define __rxor__ for reflected bitwise XOR.
#   ABCMeta is a powerful metaclass, but its entire power lies in
#   class-hierarchy machinery — not in operator overloading.
#   n ^ ABCMeta is not a valid Python expression.
# type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)) is <class 'function'>:
#   functions do not define __rxor__. Unlike some frameworks that overload
#   ^ as a composition or XOR operator, CPython's built-in function type
#   has no __rxor__. n ^ f is not a valid Python expression for callable
#   objects.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table ab3271.rxor:
  description: "abc types __rxor__ dict-presence checks; wave 665"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: ab3271

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["ab3271007", operator.contains, [abc.ABC.__dict__,                                 "__rxor__"], false]
    - ["ab3271008", operator.contains, [abc.ABCMeta.__dict__,                             "__rxor__"], false]
    - ["ab3271009", operator.contains, [type(abc.abstractmethod(lambda: None)).__dict__,  "__rxor__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# combined — __rand__, __ror__, __rxor__ across all 3 abc subjects
#
# Covers the full matrix: 3 classes x 3 methods = 9 rows.
# __rand__: false for all 3.
# __ror__: false for all 3.
# __rxor__: false for all 3.
# All 9 values are false.
# Continues the all-false pattern from wave 664 (__rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__).
# The function type profile across all waves tested:
#   true:  __get__ (652), __repr__ (655), __call__ (656)
#   false: __set__, __delete__, __hash__, __eq__, __bool__, __lt__, __le__, __gt__,
#          __ge__, __str__, __len__, __getitem__, __setitem__, __delitem__,
#          __contains__, __add__, __sub__, __mul__, __truediv__, __floordiv__,
#          __mod__, __pow__, __lshift__, __rshift__, __and__, __or__, __xor__,
#          __radd__, __rsub__, __rmul__, __rtruediv__, __rfloordiv__, __rmod__,
#          __rpow__, __rlshift__, __rrshift__, __rand__, __ror__, __rxor__
# The function type is tightly scoped to its role as a callable descriptor with
#   a display representation. All arithmetic, bitwise, reflected arithmetic,
#   reflected power/shift, and reflected bitwise logical operators are absent.
# abc.ABCMeta note: ABCMeta has now returned false for every arithmetic,
#   bitwise, and reflected dunder tested across 14 consecutive waves (652–665).
#   Its power lies exclusively in class-hierarchy machinery — not in operator
#   overloading of any kind.
# abc.ABC note: ABC is a pure syntactic convenience for declaring abstract base
#   classes. It has no state of its own beyond what ABCMeta provides, and defines
#   no arithmetic, bitwise, reflected arithmetic, power/shift, or reflected
#   bitwise logical protocol whatsoever.
# Cross-wave summary for abc subjects:
#   Wave 652 (ab3076): __get__ true for function type; __set__/__delete__ false.
#   Wave 653 (ab3091): __hash__/__eq__/__bool__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 654 (ab3106): __lt__/__le__/__gt__ all false for all 3.
#   Wave 655 (ab3121): __ge__ false; __repr__ true for function type only; __str__ false.
#   Wave 656 (ab3136): __call__ true for function type only; __len__/__getitem__ false.
#   Wave 657 (ab3151): __setitem__/__delitem__/__contains__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 658 (ab3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 659 (ab3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 660 (ab3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 661 (ab3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 662 (ab3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 663 (ab3241): __rtruediv__/__rfloordiv__/__rmod__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 664 (ab3256): __rpow__/__rlshift__/__rrshift__ — all false for all 3.
#   Wave 665 (ab3271): __rand__/__ror__/__rxor__ — all false for all 3.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

